'''Tomari Shrine''' (とまりじんじゃ) is a {{ill|lt=Shinto shrine|Q845945|WD=Q845945|1=Shinto shrine}} on {{ill|lt=Shikine-jima|Q1344326|WD=Q1344326|1=Shikine-jima}}, southwest of {{ill|lt=Niijima, Tokyo|Q1204534|WD=Q1204534|1=Niijima, Tokyo}}, {{ill|lt=Tokyo|Q1490|WD=Q1490|1=Tokyo}}.

It is identified with '''Kunitsuhime-no-Mikoto Shrine''' (くにつひめのみことじんじゃ), a {{ill|UNKNOWN|lt=Shikinaisha|1=Shikinaisha|WD=Q134917286}}<ref name="yao">[https://yaokami.jp/1131744/ 泊神社] - Yaoyorozu no Kami</ref>.

=== Overview ===
Its founding is unknown, but as it is identified with a Shikinaisha, its origin goes back to at least ancient times.

In {{ill|lt=1912|Q2077|WD=Q2077|1=1912}} (Meiji 45), it was moved to the current site while enshrining other deities together<ref name="kanko">[https://shikinejima.tokyo/learn/historic/historic_place/1062/ 泊神社] - Shikinejima Tourism Association</ref>.

The name "Tomari Shrine" began to be used in {{ill|lt=1953|Q18585|WD=Q18585|1=1953}} (Shōwa 28), and from {{ill|lt=1960|Q3754|WD=Q3754|1=1960}} (Shōwa 35) onward repairs to the worship hall and new construction of a kagura hall were carried out step by step, forming its present layout<ref name="kanko"/>.

=== Enshrined deity ===
* Tomari Mitokuchi Ōkisaki Myōjin (みとのくち おおきさきみょうじん) - Kunitsuhime-no-Mikoto, consort of {{ill|WD=Q8009611|lt=Kotoshironushi|Q8009611|WD=Q8009611|1=Kotoshironushi-no-Mikoto}}<ref name="yao"/><ref name="kanko"/>.

